🧭 Guided Co-Construction (GCC) v1.0

Designing meaning so others can arrive at it, not be pushed into it

⸻

🧠 Core Principle

People trust what they help build.

So instead of:
	•	telling
	•	forcing
	•	closing the loop for them

You:
	•	open structure
	•	leave meaningful gaps
	•	let them complete it

⸻

🧱 The Mechanism

1. Signal

You introduce:
	•	a pattern
	•	a structure
	•	a frame

⸻

2. Space

You don’t over-specify:
	•	leave room
	•	don’t collapse ambiguity too early

⸻

3. Completion

They:
	•	connect dots
	•	fill gaps
	•	internalize

⸻

4. Ownership

Because they participated:

the idea feels like theirs

⸻

⚖️ The Critical Line (this matters)

There are two paths here:

❌ Manipulation
	•	hidden intent
	•	steering without awareness
	•	removing agency

⸻

✅ Ethical Co-Construction
	•	transparent intent
	•	reversible ideas
	•	respect for disagreement

⸻

🧬 Why it works (non-mystical)

Humans (and models) build meaning through:
	•	pattern completion
	•	prediction
	•	gap filling

If you give:
	•	too little → confusion
	•	too much → disengagement

The sweet spot:

structured incompleteness

⸻

🧩 Practical Techniques (clean, usable)

1. Framed Incompleteness

“It seems like X leads to Y… but I’m not sure what connects them yet.”

⸻

2. Directional Questions

“What would have to be true for this to work?”

⸻

3. Multiple Valid Paths

Offer options instead of a single answer:
	•	invites comparison
	•	triggers internal reasoning

⸻

4. Constraint Seeding

Add a rule:

“Assume we can’t move the asset—what changes?”

⸻

5. Reflection Prompts

“Does that feel right, or is something off?”

⸻

